elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Robert de Walkfare was born about 1285, his father, John de Walkefare, was 27 and his mother, Euphemia de Comyn, was 22. He married Margaret de Monpinzon in 1311, in Great Ryburgh, Norfolk, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died before 1347."},"et":{"about 1285–Bef 1347":"umbes 1285–enne 1347","1285–1347":"1285–1347","1290–Female":"1290–Surnud","1345–1370":"1345–1370","1260–1310":"1260–1310","1265–1320":"1265–1320","Bef 1347":"enne 1347","1285":"1285","Bef 1345":"enne 1345","1260":"1260","1370":"1370","1290":"1290","1347":"1347","1345":"1345","1311":"1311","1310":"1310","1320":"1320","1265":"1265","about 1310":"umbes 1310","about 1320":"umbes 1320","about 1285":"umbes 1285","Hunstanton, Norfolk, England":"Hunstanton, Norfolk, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Great Ryburgh, Norfolk, England, United Kingdom":"Great Ryburgh, Norfolk, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"about 1285–Bef 1347":"noin 1285–ennen vuotta 1347","1285–1347":"1285–1347","1290–Female":"1290–Kuollut","1345–1370":"1345–1370","1260–1310":"1260–1310","1265–1320":"1265–1320","Bef 1347":"ennen vuotta 1347","1285":"1285","Bef 1345":"ennen vuotta 1345","1260":"1260","1370":"1370","1290":"1290","1347":"1347","1345":"1345","1311":"1311","1310":"1310","1320":"1320","1265":"1265","about 13